Trump and the Economy
New York — Financial markets finally woke up to the fact that Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured the unchecked tweets and public statements from this most powerful person on the globe for two years, and the obvious question is, what has kept this going for so long?
On one hand, up to now, investors have been treating Trump as a thunder without rain.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies favorable to the corporate sector and shareholders, they are willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many believe that, in the end, the "adults in the room" will rein in Trump, ensuring government policies stay within bounds.
This assumption was more or less confirmed during Trump's first year in office, a period during which economic growth and expected corporate profit increases — thanks to the upcoming tax cuts and deregulation — led to strong stock market performance.
In 2017, U.S. stock indices rose by more than 20%.
But in 2018, the situation turned sharply downward, especially in the last few months.
Although corporate profits increased by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the U.S. stock market fluctuated for most of the year and then plunged sharply.
Currently, various indices are in a correction phase (i.e., down 10% from the most recent high), with tech indices (such as the NASDAQ) having dropped into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Although increased market volatility reflects concerns over China, Italy, and other Eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turbulence was due to Trump.
This year started with Trump implementing reckless tax cuts, which pushed up long-term interest rates and pushed the economy, which was already near full employment, to a peak.
By February, concerns over inflation rising above the Fed's target of 2% triggered the first risk-off surge of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important U.S. trade partners.
Concerns about government protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year, but are now reaching a new high.
Recent actions by the United States toward China seem to be preparing for a comprehensive trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies could lead to stagflation (weakened growth and increased inflation).
After all, Trump is ready to limit foreign direct investment inflows and has implemented extensive immigration restrictions, which will hinder the growth of labor supply in the context of increasingly severe labor aging and skill mismatches.
Additionally, the Trump administration has not yet proposed a plan to stimulate productivity in the private sector or accelerate the infrastructure plan for the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other occasions, Trump continuously attacks the hiring, production, investment, and pricing behaviors of companies, especially technology companies, which have already faced widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also been impacted by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening have raised both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies have experienced capital outflows and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies that heavily rely on exports have suffered losses due to falling commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade relations with China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy created volatility.
The U.S. reimposing sanctions on Iran raised oil prices, and afterward, the U.S. government revoked exemptions and pressured Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, causing oil prices to plummet.
Although American consumers benefited from low oil prices, American energy company stock prices could not withstand the pressure.
Additionally, excessive oil price volatility is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hinders wise investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, now it's clear that almost all the benefits from last year's tax cuts have flowed to the corporate sector, rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means that household consumption may soon slow down, further affecting the economy.
However, the main cause of the recent quarter's暴跌 in American and global stock markets is Trump himself and his remarks and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (although he recently reached a "truce" with President Xi Jinping of China) is Trump's open criticism of the Federal Reserve. His attacks began in the spring of 2018, when the U.S. GDP growth rate was above 4%.
Due to these earlier attacks, the market became skittish when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates this month, while signaling that it would raise rates more slowly in 2019.
More likely, the Federal Reserve's relatively hawkish stance is a response to Trump's attacks on it.
Jerome Powell, the Federal Reserve Chair, needs to send a signal that the central bank still maintains political independence in the face of an antagonistic presidential tweet.
But then, because Congress refused to fund Trump's useless border wall with Mexico, Trump decided to shut down the federal government partially.
This move put the market into a state of near panic, as reports quickly emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could turn market corrections into a full-blown crash.
Just before the Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to calm the market.
He claimed that Trump has no plan to fire Powell, and that the U.S. fiscal situation is good — which ironically highlights the very question of whether the situation is truly good.
Government personnel changes within the administration that may not affect economic decisions have recently caused market concerns.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave, and the Trump cabinet will no longer have any sane individuals.
The remaining members will all be economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks who will follow Trump's lead.
The possibility of all-out geopolitical confrontation with China still cannot be ruled out.
A new Cold War is likely to lead to deglobalization and disrupt global supply chains, but the tech industry will be hit first, as evidenced by the recent ZTE and Huawei cases.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO during a period of economic and political instability in Europe.
Special Prosecutor Robert Mueller's investigation into Trump's 2016 campaign's ties with Russia serves as a Damocles sword hanging over Trump's presidency.
Trump is now the Oddfather of the financial markets.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in a mutually assured economic destruction.
Now, the market has seen this danger, with the risk of financial crisis and global recession rising steadily.
